[ASSISTANT] In ExoPlayer, you can set a minimum bitrate for adaptive streaming by configuring the `DefaultTrackSelector`. The `DefaultTrackSelector` is responsible for selecting the appropriate media track based on the available options and the playback conditions.

To set a minimum bitrate, you can use the `setMinVideoBitrate` method of the `DefaultTrackSelector.Parameters` class. Here's an example:

```java
DefaultTrackSelector.ParametersBuilder builder = new DefaultTrackSelector.ParametersBuilder(/* context */);
builder.setMinVideoBitrate(/* minimum bitrate */);
DefaultTrackSelector.Parameters parameters = builder.build();

DefaultTrackSelector trackSelector = new DefaultTrackSelector(/* context */);
trackSelector.setParameters(parameters);
```

In the code snippet above, `setMinVideoBitrate` is used to specify the minimum video bitrate in bits per second. You can replace `/* minimum bitrate */` with the desired value.

Once you have configured the `DefaultTrackSelector` with the desired parameters, you can set it to your `SimpleExoPlayer` instance:

```java
SimpleExoPlayer player = new SimpleExoPlayer.Builder(/* context */).setTrackSelector(trackSelector).build();
```

By setting a minimum bitrate, ExoPlayer will try to select a video track that has a bitrate higher than or equal to the specified minimum. This helps ensure that the video quality doesn't drop below a certain threshold, even in situations with limited network bandwidth.

